{"name":"Odell 90 Shilling clone", "source":"http://www.homebrewdenver.com/2013/03/clone-brew-odell-90-shilling/", "description":"<p style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; padding: 5px 0px; font-size: 12px; color: #666666; font-family: Arial; line-height: 20.4px;\">The folks at Odell Brewing Company were nice enough to hook us up with the recipe for one of their most popular beers, 90 Shilling. This easy drinking Scottish Ale drinks like a big, malty American Amber Ale &ndash; perfect for those cold days ahead before Spring arrives. Although it doesn&rsquo;t fit cleanly into a BJCP style, 90 Shilling has taken home awards in multiple categories, including a Great American Beer Festival Gold in 1991. A World-Class score on BeerAdvocate (97) doesn&rsquo;t hurt either. For those of you that have never had 90 Shilling, or if you&rsquo;ve just plain forgotten what it tastes like, here are our thoughts.</p>\n<p style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; padding: 5px 0px; font-size: 12px; color: #666666; font-family: Arial; line-height: 20.4px;\"><strong style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\">Aroma &ndash;</strong>&nbsp;Fairly subdued nose with a slight caramel hit, followed by biscuity malt and citrus hop notes.</p>\n<p style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; padding: 5px 0px; font-size: 12px; color: #666666; font-family: Arial; line-height: 20.4px;\"><strong style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\">Taste &ndash;</strong>&nbsp;As you&rsquo;d expect, 90 Shilling has a big malt backbone with a moderate caramel sweetness. The flavor quickly changes into a light earthy bitterness and finishes just dry enough to make you want to have another sip. And another&hellip;</p>\n<p style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; padding: 5px 0px; font-size: 12px; color: #666666; font-family: Arial; line-height: 20.4px;\"><strong style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px;\">Mouthfeel &ndash;</strong>&nbsp;Medium body, moderate carbonation (shoot for around 2.5 volumes CO2&nbsp;given the style).</p>\n<h4 style=\"border: 0px; margin: 15px 0px 2px; padding: 0px 0px 2px; font-size: 1.333em; line-height: 1.5em; font-weight: normal; font-family: Oswald; color: #444444;\">Notes:</h4>\n<ul>\n<li style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; padding: 5px 0px; font-size: 12px; color: #666666; font-family: Arial; line-height: 20.4px;\">Mash at 152 degrees for 60 minutes</li>\n<li style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; padding: 5px 0px; font-size: 12px; color: #666666; font-family: Arial; line-height: 20.4px;\">Boil for 90 minutes.</li>\n<li style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; padding: 5px 0px; font-size: 12px; color: #666666; font-family: Arial; line-height: 20.4px;\">Cool to 67 and pitch starter.</li>\n<li style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px 0px 5px; padding: 5px 0px; font-size: 12px; color: #666666; font-family: Arial; line-height: 20.4px;\">Ferment for approximately 7-10 days then rack to secondary for 2 weeks.</li>\n</ul>", "style":"14", "subtype":"C", "originalGravity":"1.068", "boilTime":"90", "maltAdditions":[{"pounds":10, "remainingMinutes":90, "label":"2-Row", "triple":{"subject":"urn:uuid:d5a0e6e8-c0bb-4e99-bb75-187df6c43b78", "predicate":"http://davidcassel.net/beer/malt#addition", "object":"http://davidcassel.net/beer/malt#2-row"}}, {"pounds":1, "remainingMinutes":90, "label":"Munich (10L°)", "triple":{"subject":"urn:uuid:d5a0e6e8-c0bb-4e99-bb75-187df6c43b78", "predicate":"http://davidcassel.net/beer/malt#addition", "object":"http://davidcassel.net/beer/malt#munich-10"}}, {"pounds":0.5, "remainingMinutes":90, "label":"Crystal (20L°)", "triple":{"subject":"urn:uuid:d5a0e6e8-c0bb-4e99-bb75-187df6c43b78", "predicate":"http://davidcassel.net/beer/malt#addition", "object":"http://davidcassel.net/beer/malt#crystal-20"}}, {"pounds":0.5, "remainingMinutes":90, "label":"Crystal (80L°)", "triple":{"subject":"urn:uuid:d5a0e6e8-c0bb-4e99-bb75-187df6c43b78", "predicate":"http://davidcassel.net/beer/malt#addition", "object":"http://da